The '''Canada Temperance Act''' was an Act of the  in 1878, which provided for an option for municipalities to opt-in by  to a prohibitionary scheme. It was often known as the '''Scott Act''', on account of its sponsor Sir . 
The Act was based on similar provincial legislation known as the , passed in 1864, which gave the power to communities to enact prohibition.
The Act was subject to several of the first constitutional challenges, starting with '''' (1882).
The Act was later amended in 1927, and subsequently challenged again in '''' (1946).
 